AB  - This paper is concerned with regression models having heteroscedastic errors whose variances are not precisely known but can be ordered by size. The object is to use this limited information to devise regression coefficient estimators which are more efficient in finite samples than the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator. Three common relative efficiency measures (determinant, trace, and extreme eigenvalue) are considered. A class of weighted least squares (WLS) estimators is proved to be efficient relative to the OLS estimator on the determinant (generalized variance) measure. Only a partial result can be obtained for the trace measure. A counterexample shows that no similar results are possible for the eigenvalue measure under the weak conditions of this paper. The efficiency value of additional prior information on variance is also investigated.
ER  - 

